children.subject: <md>To add on to this, it's probably not a bad idea to (re-)take 61B. 61B is one of the most important classes in Berkeley CS, and you will learn a lot especially from Professor Hug.</md>
You should make an appointment with a Computer Science Advisor to have that question answered. Search for their page on the EECS.BEREKELY.EDU website.

Thanks! I was just asking since a class I've taken is equivalent to CS 9G, so I was curious whether or not I'd still have to take a new course to fulfill the requirement. I also saw on the CS61b Fall 2019 General Course Information page that it mentioned:

"Some of you may have already had a data structures course, and simply want to learn Java or C++. For you, self-study may be a better option. CS 9F (C++ for programmers) and CS 9G (Java for programmers) are both one-unit self-paced courses that will teach you more of what you want to know in less time. There is no enrollment limit for those courses, and you work through them at your own pace."

I just want to double check what this means. Is it saying CS9G is an option for expanding our knowledge in Java but it doesn't count toward completing CS61B?

history.content:
Hello! I’m currently an incoming student (intended CS), and I saw that I had completed a course that is partially equivalent to CS 61B at a local Community College (according to assist.org). I have taken that course in Java.

When I come to Berkeley this Fall, what course would I need to take to complete the CS61B requirement? Would I have to take CS 47B? Or would CS9G also suffice?
history.subject: CS 47B or CS 9G? Can I choose?
